text.tspan: Consider a PKN. For the upstream node (blue), we have proteomics information about the most abundant receptor(s). For the downstream
measurements (yellow), we have TF activity estimates inferred from transcriptomics data. Lastly, we have phosphoproteomics data reporting
about the phosphorylation status of some nodes in the PKN.
We can now compute an average activity value for the recovered kinases, for each of the two networks, and an overall average
kinase activity value. Under these assumptions, good performance is reached when a method recoveres the most active kinases, a sign that
a specific path is especially active in the context of a perturbation. In other words, methods must maximise the difference between average
